{"timestamp": "2026-07-16T14:54:39.852036+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.agents.response", "message": "answer generated", "correlation_id": "9a3dc31f-0f1d-459e-b4e6-9f05e18afaf0", "query": "What controls apply to API security?", "citations": ["ia-9", "sc-8.1", "sc-8", "sc-8.2", "sc-16.3", "sc-21", "ac-3.12", "ac-4.17", "ac-4.22", "ac-17.4", "sc-3.5", "si-10.6", "si-10.2"], "answer_chars": 2624, "input_tokens": 783, "output_tokens": 486}
{"timestamp": "2026-07-16T14:54:39.904709+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.orchestrator", "message": "query answered", "correlation_id": "9a3dc31f-0f1d-459e-b4e6-9f05e18afaf0", "query": "What controls apply to API security?", "answer": "Applicable controls for API security from the supplied list are:\n\n- Require strong identification/authentication of services and apps that communicate via APIs: uniquely identify and authenticate system services and applications before establishing communications [ia-9].\n\n- Protect confidentiality and integrity of API traffic in transit: implement cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized disclosure and to detect changes during transmission [sc-8.1], and more generally protect confidentiality and/or integrity of transmitted information [sc-8]. Also maintain confidentiality and integrity during preparation for transmission and reception (pre/post handling) [sc-8.2]. Where needed, bind security or privacy attributes to the transmitted API data (cryptographic binding) [sc-16.3].\n\n- Ensure name/address resolution used by APIs is trustworthy: request and perform data origin authentication and integrity verification on name/address resolution responses (secure resolver) to avoid DNS-based attacks on API endpoints [sc-21].\n\n- Enforce application-level access controls for API clients/consumers: require applications to assert needed access at installation, provide enforcement to prevent unauthorized access, and approve access changes after installation [ac-3.12]. Also support domain-level authentication of source and destination points for information transfer (identify/authenticate organization/system/application/service/individual) [ac-4.17].\n\n- Limit cross-domain information flow for multi-domain access scenarios: provide access from a single device to resources in multiple security domains while preventing information flow between domains (useful for APIs bridging domains) [ac-4.22].\n\n- Control privileged remote API actions: authorize privileged commands and access via remote access only in formats that provide assessable evidence, and document remote access rationale in the system security plan [ac-17.4].\n\n- Architect APIs with layered security: implement security functions in layered structures minimizing inter-layer interactions and avoiding lower-layer dependence on higher-layer correctness [sc-3.5].\n\n- Validate and sanitize inputs to APIs to prevent injections and resolve input validation errors promptly: prevent untrusted data injections [si-10.6] and review/resolve input validation errors within an organization-defined time period [si-10.2].\n\nIf you need mapping of these controls to specific API safeguards (e.g., TLS for transport, mTLS for service auth, input validation libraries, API gateway enforcement), say so and I will map each control to those concrete measures.", "latency_ms": 11041.8, "document_count": 13, "citations": ["ia-9", "sc-8.1", "sc-8", "sc-8.2", "sc-16.3", "sc-21", "ac-3.12", "ac-4.17", "ac-4.22", "ac-17.4", "sc-3.5", "si-10.6", "si-10.2"], "is_fallback": false}
